ay be from ancient Germanic <i>Aveza</i>, but more probably from Latin <i>Avitia</i> (also found in a masculine form, <i>Avitius</i>). In France, this surname is rare.","Portuguese and Spanish: habitational name from the little town of Avis (the stress is on the <i>i</i>) in Portalegre district (Portugal). This surname is found in the neighboring Spanish Extremadura.","Dutch: variant of <b>Aafjes</b> a metronymic from the female personal name <i>Ave</i>, which is of unclear origin."],"variants":[{"name":"Avins","meanings":["English: metronymic from the Middle English female personal name <i>Avine</i>, which is probably a pet form of   Avis  ."]},{"name":"Havis","meanings":["English: variant of   Avis   with prosthetic <i>H-</i>."]},{"name":"Avison","meanings":["English (Yorkshire): metronymic from the Middle English female personal name <i>Avice</i> (see   Avis  )."]},{"name":"Havice","meanings":["Perhaps an altered form of English   Avis  ."]},{"name":"Avon","meanings":["English:","habitational name from Avon (Wiltshire) or Little or Middle Avon (Gloucestershire), both named from the river on which they stand, or possibly a habitational name from a settlement on one of the rivers or small streams called Avon or Aven. These river names derive from the Celtic word for ‘river’, as reflected in Welsh <i>afon</i> and Gaelic <i>abhainn</i>. The modern surname is concentrated in Somerset and Wiltshire, England, suggesting it is associated chiefly with the Avon river that rises on the Gloucester-Wiltshire border and flows through Wiltshire and Somerset into the Severn.","from the Middle English female personal name <i>Avine</i>, which is probably a pet form of   Avis  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":39,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705202,"age":48,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705205,"age":59,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs Thomas Avis was born about 1510, in England. She had at least 1 daughter with Mr Thomas Avis."},"et":{"abt 1510–":"umbes 1510–Surnud","1510–Male":"1510–Surnud","1538–1638":"1538–1638","1510–Female":"1510–Surnud","abt 1510":"umbes 1510","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1510":"1510","1638":"1638","1538":"1538","1549":"1549","Bradfield St Clare, Suffolk, England":"Bradfield St Clare, Suffolk, England","England":"England"},"fi":{"abt 1510–":"noin 1510–Kuollut","1510–Male":"1510–Kuollut","1538–1638":"1538–1638","1510–Female":"1510–Kuollut","abt 1510":"noin 15